  "articleSummary": "The article argues that multiple-choice questions (MCQs), often dismissed as simplistic, are a powerful tool for deep learning when designed with intentional \"distractors\" (wrong answers) that reflect real misconceptions. Focusing on programming education, it highlights how well-crafted MCQs can reveal learners’ mental models, differentiate expertise levels, and force instructors to clarify concepts—using PostgreSQL syntax as an example. The author emphasizes that effective MCQs require modeling common errors, turning the format into a feedback loop that sharpens both teaching and learning. The tone is analytical and reflective, blending personal insight with practical advice for educators and technical content creators. Key metaphors include \"the distractor is the curriculum\" and framing MCQs",
